{
  "name": "Work on GitHub Issue",
  "version": "2.0.0",
  "description": "Fetches open issues from the current GitHub repository, lets the user pick one, and then guides the agent through implementing it using the correct Kiro spec workflow based on issue type.",
  "when": {
    "type": "userTriggered"
  },
  "then": {
    "type": "askAgent",
    "prompt": "The user wants to work on a GitHub issue. Follow this workflow exactly:\n\n## Step 1: Fetch Issues\n\n1. Determine the current repository's GitHub owner and repo name from `git remote -v`.\n2. Use the GitHub MCP tools to list open issues for this repository, sorted by creation date descending (most recent first), limited to 10.\n3. If there are NO open issues, tell the user there are no open issues and stop.\n\n## Step 2: Present Issues to the User\n\n- If there is exactly ONE open issue: display its title, number, and a brief summary of the body. Ask the user: \"This is the only open issue. Would you like me to work on this?\"\n- If there are MULTIPLE open issues: display the 10 most recently created issues as a numbered list showing `#<number> — <title>`. Ask the user to pick one by number. After the user picks one, fetch the full issue details (title, body, labels, comments) and display them. Then ask: \"Would you like me to work on this issue?\"\n\n## Step 3: Wait for Confirmation\n\nDo NOT proceed until the user explicitly confirms they want you to work on the selected issue. If the user says no or picks a different issue, go back to the selection step.\n\n## Step 4: Classify the Issue Type\n\nOnce the user confirms, determine the issue type from its labels, title, and body:\n\n- **Bug**: The issue describes something broken, incorrect, or behaving unexpectedly. Look for labels like `bug`, or language describing incorrect behaviour, errors, crashes, or regressions.\n- **Feature or Task**: The issue describes new functionality, an enhancement, a refactoring task, or any work that is not a bug fix. This includes labels like `enhancement`, `feature`, `task`, or any issue that is not a bug.\n\nThe issue type determines which Kiro spec workflow to use. This is non-negotiable.\n\n## Step 5: Assess Complexity\n\nAssess the complexity of the issue:\n\n### Very Simple\nThe change is obvious, localised to one or two files, and requires no design decisions. Examples: fixing a typo, updating a version number, adding a single field, renaming something.\n\n- You MUST tell the user: \"This looks like a very simple change. I can implement it directly without creating a spec. Are you happy for me to proceed in vibe-coding mode?\"\n- Only proceed with direct implementation if the user explicitly agrees.\n- If the user says no, treat it as Simple instead.\n\n### Simple\nWell-defined and self-contained but involves enough work that a plan is useful. Examples: adding a new small feature, fixing a bug with a clear root cause, refactoring a single module.\n\n- Create a spec directory under `.kiro/specs/` named after the issue.\n- Create ALL THREE spec files in a single pass, then present the full spec to the user for review.\n- For bugs: create `bugfix.md`, `design.md`, and `tasks.md` together.\n- For features/tasks: create `requirements.md`, `design.md`, and `tasks.md` together.\n- Ask: \"Here is the full spec. Would you like to refine anything, or shall I proceed with implementation?\"\n- Iterate if the user requests changes. Once confirmed, implement all tasks.\n\n### Complex\nLarge, ambiguous, has multiple possible approaches, or spans many files/modules. Examples: adding a major feature, redesigning a subsystem, implementing a new workflow.\n\n- Create a spec directory under `.kiro/specs/` named after the issue.\n- Follow the FULL spec-driven development workflow with user confirmation at each stage.\n- The first file depends on the issue type (see Step 6). Present it and wait for confirmation before proceeding to the next file.\n\n## Step 6: Execute the Correct Spec Workflow\n\nThe spec workflow is determined by the issue type from Step 4. You MUST use the correct workflow.\n\n### For Bug Issues: Bugfix Spec Workflow\n\nBugs ALWAYS use the Bugfix Spec workflow. The first file is `bugfix.md`, not `requirements.md`.\n\n`bugfix.md` must capture:\n- **Current Behavior (Defect)**: WHEN [condition] THEN the system [incorrect behavior]\n- **Expected Behavior (Correct)**: WHEN [condition] THEN the system SHALL [correct behavior]\n- **Unchanged Behavior (Regression Prevention)**: WHEN [condition] THEN the system SHALL CONTINUE TO [existing behavior]\n\nWorkflow order: `bugfix.md` → `design.md` → `tasks.md`\n\nFor Simple bugs: create all three files at once, present for review, then implement.\nFor Complex bugs: create `bugfix.md` first, get confirmation, then `design.md`, get confirmation, then `tasks.md`, get confirmation, then implement.\n\n### For Feature or Task Issues: Requirements-First Workflow\n\nFeatures and tasks ALWAYS use the Requirements-First workflow. The first file is `requirements.md`.\n\n`requirements.md` must capture requirements using EARS notation:\n- WHEN [condition/event] THE SYSTEM SHALL [expected behavior]\n\nWorkflow order: `requirements.md` → `design.md` → `tasks.md`\n\nFor Simple features/tasks: create all three files at once, present for review, then implement.\nFor Complex features/tasks: create `requirements.md` first, get confirmation, then `design.md`, get confirmation, then `tasks.md`, get confirmation, then implement.\n\n## Rules\n\n1. NEVER skip the issue selection and confirmation steps.\n2. NEVER start implementation without the user confirming the approach.\n3. For very simple tasks, you MUST get explicit permission for vibe-coding mode.\n4. Bug issues MUST use the Bugfix Spec workflow (`bugfix.md` → `design.md` → `tasks.md`). NEVER create `requirements.md` for a bug.\n5. Feature and task issues MUST use the Requirements-First workflow (`requirements.md` → `design.md` → `tasks.md`). NEVER create `bugfix.md` for a feature or task.\n6. If you are unsure about complexity, default to the Simple approach.\n7. If you are unsure whether an issue is a bug or feature, ask the user.\n8. Reference the issue number in commit messages when making changes."
  }
}
